<HEADLINE>
<P>
WINDS CARVE DAMAGE SWATH IN NORTHWEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Storms on Monday brought heavy rains and 100-m.p.h. winds to the Northwest. 
Utility lines were ripped down, houses were smashed and fallen trees and 
rockslides blocked highways. 
</P>
<P>
Gusts up to 107 m.p.h. toppled nearly 100 trees and ripped off roofs on the 
Washington State University campus at Pullman, near the Idaho border. 
</P>
<P>
Joseph Spoonemore, the university's physical plant director, said the wind 
broke windows in a dozen buildings and blew the roofs off several others, 
including a dormitory, but most students were off campus for winter break. He 
estimated the damage at $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
Oregon coastal communities shuddered in gusts up to 76 m.p.h. early Monday and 
were braced for a third windstorm. 
</P>
<P>
Utility crews scrambled to remove tree limbs from power lines and replace 
toppled poles in much of the state. 
</P>
<P>
Winds of up to 70 m.p.h. also swooped down the Columbia Gorge, knocked out 
electricity and phone service in the Tri-Cities region of southern Washington 
and, farther east, in border areas from Spokane, Wash., south to Lewiston, Ida. 
</P>
</TEXT>
