<HEADLINE>
<P>
AFTER HEART SURGERY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I had a bypass operation close to a year ago. Shortly after, my 
doctor recommended that I get involved in a cardiac rehabilitation program, but 
I guess I was too upset at the time to do anything about it. 
</P>
<P>
I'm sorry now that I didn't, and I'd like to know if such a program would do me 
any good if I got into one now. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: The results of one study suggest that patients can benefit from a 
cardiac rehabilitation program even if they enter one up to two years after 
having had a heart attack or bypass surgery. However, those who begin 
participating in such a program within six months of the event do appear to 
realize greater benefits from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
