<SUBJECT>
<P>
UNITED STATES -- ECONOMY; CONSUMER CREDIT 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010990-0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 159503 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 9, 1990, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
97 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Continental Cuts Fares Again: Continental Airlines, which last week raised 
fares by 4%, said it would offer one-way tickets to and from Texas cities for 
as low as $9 to fill seats that otherwise would be empty. "It's a whole lot 
more productive to put somebody in a seat at $9 or $19 than to have that seat 
go empty," said John Nelson, Continental's executive vice president of 
marketing. The new fares, dubbed "TexSavers," are good for travel between all 
Texas cities Continental serves, except El Paso, and for travel between Houston 
and New Orleans, Oklahoma City and Tulsa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
