<HEADLINE>
<P>
GIRLS' ATHLETE OF THE WEEK: GANDARA IS THE TOP GUN AT UNIVERSITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ARA NAJARIAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
IRVINE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Doug Sorey, girls' basketball coach at University High School, knows the best 
way to handle his team's best shooter, Denise Gandara. 
</P>
<P>
He lets her shoot. 
</P>
<P>
"If my team's going to get beat, then I have to get beat with (Gandara) 
shooting the ball," Sorey said. 
</P>
<P>
And that hasn't been very often. University is 10-3. 
</P>
<P>
Gandara, The Times' Athlete of the Week, scored 27 points in University's 70-19 
victory over Irvine Wednesday, and scored 26 more in a 53-36 victory over 
Woodbridge Friday. 
</P>
<P>
But before Gandara can shoot, her teammates have to get her the ball. 
University's offense revolves around that task. 
</P>
<P>
"This past summer, we had a girl transfer to our team and she didn't get the 
idea," Sorey said. "Finally I had to take her aside and say, 'Throw (Gandara) 
the ball.' " 
</P>
<P>
Still, it hasn't been easy. Not only did Sorey have to encourage Gandara's 
teammates to throw her the ball, he also had to tell her to shoot it. 
</P>
<P>
"There were a lot of good shooters last year," Gandara said. "I look to shoot 
now because I'm the only starter returning from last year." 
</P>
<P>
Gandara was a reluctant shooter last season, but Sorey was confident she would 
take the initiative this season. 
</P>
<P>
"I knew Denise would score this year, in part because she had a great summer," 
Sorey said. "In (assistant coach) Bruce Bernal, we have a great offensive 
coach. And he's encouraged Denise to shoot the last couple of years because she 
was a little reluctant. 
</P>
<P>
"She has the ability to shoot outside, put the ball on the floor and drive, and 
to post up. But I didn't dream she would be this successful." 
</P>
<P>
Gandara, a 5-foot-7 senior, does more than shoot, though. She is averaging nine 
rebounds a game. 
</P>
<P>
"She's a good offensive rebounder," Sorey said. "She has good quickness, good 
leaping ability and good hands. Defensively, she screens out real well." 
</P>
<P>
TOP PERFORMERS 
</P>
<P>
Allison Arrendondo of Los Alamitos scored 34 points, 20 in the second half, in 
a 50-47 loss to El Dorado Thursday. She had 19 of Los Alamitos' 29 points in a 
45-29 loss to Fountain Valley Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
Senior post player Nicole Champion of Orange had 26 points, nine rebounds and 
five steals against El Modena Tuesday in a 69-52 victory. She scored 15 points 
and had 11 rebounds in 61-35 victory over Sonora Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Chrissy Coppage had three goals and had three assists to lead Esperanza's 
soccer team to a 9-0 victory over Loara Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Amy Jalewalia had 34 points for La Quinta in a 76-16 victory over Pacifica 
Wednesday and had 35 points in a 62-60 overtime victory over Rancho Alamitos 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Linda Lunceford had five goals to lead Trabuco Hills' soccer team to a 9-0 
victory over Bolsa Grande Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Denise Gandara 
</P>
<P>
University High School 
</P>
<P>
* Position: Forward 
</P>
<P>
* Height, Weight, Class: 5-7, 130, Senior 
</P>
<P>
* Last Week: Gandara scored 27 points and had 13 rebounds in a 70-19 victory 
over Irvine Wednesday and added 26 points and 11 rebounds in a 53-36 victory 
over Woodbridge Friday. 
</P>
<P>
* Season: Gandara is averaging 22 points and nine rebounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
