<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 1 in 200 of the 107-million tax-form packages mailed by the IRS last 
month contained return envelopes with the wrong address, IRS spokesman Steve 
Pyrek said today. 
</P>
<P>
"For example, a taxpayer in Maryland, who normally would file to Philadelphia, 
might receive a package with an envelope carrying a Cincinnati address," Pyrek 
explained. The folks at the IRS are red-faced but say there is no reason for 
panic. He said taxpayers may change the address on the IRS envelope, but even 
if they don't, processing returns sent to the wrong address will not pose a 
problem for the IRS. 
