<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWBERY MEDAL TO LOWRY FOR CHILDREN'S BOOK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Author Lois Lowry has won the prestigious John Newbery Medal for children's 
books, while illustrator Ed Young was awarded the Randolph Caldecott Medal. 
</P>
<P>
The awards were announced Monday at an American Library Assn. meeting. 
</P>
<P>
Lowry, author of "Number the Stars," won the 1990 Newbery Medal for the most 
distinguished contribution to American literature for children published in 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
Young, illustrator of "Lon Po Po: A Red-Riding Hood Story from China," won the 
Caldecott for the most distinguished American picture book published last year. 
</P>
<P>
The awards are administered by the Assn. for Library Service to Children, a 
division of the library association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
