<P>
UPSETS MARK NEW ZEALAND OPEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Steve Guy of New Zealand upset second-seeded Czech Miloslav Mecir 6-3, 6-3 
today in the first round of the Benson and Hedges New Zealand Open tennis 
championships. He will next face compatriot Brett Steven, a 6-3, 6-0 winner 
over Finn Veli Paloheimo. 
</P>
<P>
American Glenn Layendecker also scored an upset today, ousting No. 4 seed Kelly 
Evernden of New Zealand, 6-2, 6-4. Top-seed Andrei Chesnokov of the Soviet 
Union, ranked 18th in the world, struggled past West German qualifier Marcus 
Zoecke 6-7 (5-7), 7-6 (7-4), 7-5, and American Scott Davis, the eighth seed, 
rallied to defeat Swede Christian Bergstrom 1-6, 6-4, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
Americans Jimmy Arias and Richey Reneberg also advanced to the last 16. Arias 
downed Italian Claudio Pistolesi 6-3, 6-3, and Reneberg breezed past Israeli 
Gilad Bloom 6-3, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, Australia, meanwhile, rain washed out all play today in the New 
South Wales Open tennis championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
